1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,229
Welcome to Part One of the RCC onboarding curriculum.

2
00:00:03,229 --> 00:00:10,046
This lesson is designed for biomedical researchers who may be very experienced in their scientific domain but new to

3
00:00:10,046 --> 00:00:10,763
Linux clusters.

4
00:00:10,763 --> 00:00:14,351
We will build a mental model before using any commands.

5
00:00:14,351 --> 00:00:21,168
You will see what runs on your own computer, what runs on the cluster, why secure shell is used,

6
00:00:21,168 --> 00:00:27,626
how Visual Studio Code connects, how data transfer differs from interactive login, and why Slurm controls compute jobs.

7
00:00:27,626 --> 00:00:34,083
By the end, you should be able to connect, move a small test file, submit a batch job,

8
00:00:34,083 --> 00:00:35,877
and verify where it ran.

9
00:00:35,877 --> 00:00:39,824
The examples are intentionally small and contain no sensitive research data.

10
00:00:39,824 --> 00:00:45,266
Think of the RCC as a shared scientific instrument rather than a faster desktop computer.

11
00:00:45,266 --> 00:00:47,805
The login host is the reception desk.

12
00:00:47,805 --> 00:00:53,610
It authenticates you and lets you prepare work, but it is not intended for heavy analysis.

13
00:00:53,610 --> 00:00:58,326
Compute nodes are the instruments that run CPU, memory, or GPU intensive jobs.

14
00:00:58,326 --> 00:01:00,865
Shared storage holds project data and results.

15
00:01:00,865 --> 00:01:06,670
Slurm is the booking and scheduling system that decides when and where a job can run.

16
00:01:06,670 --> 00:01:10,298
This separation protects other users and makes large analyses repeatable.

17
00:01:10,298 --> 00:01:17,190
A command typed in the wrong place can affect many people, so every tutorial will tell you where a

18
00:01:17,190 --> 00:01:19,730
command runs and what success looks like.

19
00:01:19,730 --> 00:01:24,078
A major source of confusion is the local and remote split.

20
00:01:24,078 --> 00:01:28,030
Your keyboard, web browser, and normal desktop applications are local.

21
00:01:28,030 --> 00:01:34,354
When secure shell is connected, the terminal prompt is remote and commands execute on the RCC.

22
00:01:34,354 --> 00:01:41,864
Visual Studio Code also has two sides: the graphical application remains on your laptop, while its remote extension starts

23
00:01:41,864 --> 00:01:45,422
helper processes on the cluster and opens remote files.

24
00:01:45,422 --> 00:01:50,560
Always inspect the hostname, current directory, and prompt before deleting or moving files.

25
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:56,489
A file in Downloads on Windows or macOS is not automatically visible on RCC storage.

26
00:01:56,489 --> 00:02:00,046
It must be transferred through an approved transfer mechanism.

27
00:02:00,046 --> 00:02:06,162
Secure Shell, usually called S S H, provides an encrypted channel between your computer and the cluster.

28
00:02:06,162 --> 00:02:09,760
Encryption protects credentials and commands while they travel across networks.

29
00:02:09,760 --> 00:02:14,077
An SSH key pair has a private key and a public key.

30
00:02:14,077 --> 00:02:16,955
The private key stays on your own computer.

31
00:02:16,955 --> 00:02:19,833
The public key can be registered with RCC.

32
00:02:19,833 --> 00:02:26,669
During login, the two sides prove that the correct private key is present without sending that private key to

33
00:02:26,669 --> 00:02:27,388
the server.

34
00:02:27,388 --> 00:02:31,346
A passphrase protects the private key if the laptop is lost.

35
00:02:31,346 --> 00:02:36,383
Store that passphrase in an approved password manager before you finish creating the key.

36
00:02:36,383 --> 00:02:38,901
Never email or upload the private key.

37
00:02:38,901 --> 00:02:43,923
On Windows, use a current supported version with the built-in OpenSSH client.

38
00:02:43,923 --> 00:02:47,690
PowerShell is the simplest terminal for the first test.

39
00:02:47,690 --> 00:02:51,876
On macOS, the Terminal application already includes an SSH client.

40
00:02:51,876 --> 00:02:58,991
Install the desktop version of Visual Studio Code and then install the Microsoft Remote - SSH extension.

41
00:02:58,991 --> 00:03:00,246
The sequence matters.

42
00:03:00,246 --> 00:03:03,595
First prove that the command line connection works.

43
00:03:03,595 --> 00:03:09,454
Only then configure VS Code, because the editor uses the same SSH configuration underneath.

44
00:03:09,454 --> 00:03:11,965
This makes errors easier to diagnose.

45
00:03:11,965 --> 00:03:18,662
Keep your operating system updated and do not install keys or configuration files from untrusted sources.

46
00:03:18,662 --> 00:03:23,286
The RCC connection may use a gateway before reaching the submission host.

47
00:03:23,286 --> 00:03:28,295
ProxyJump tells SSH to authenticate through the gateway while preserving end-to-end SSH behavior.

48
00:03:28,295 --> 00:03:34,076
A small configuration file gives the route a memorable alias such as R C C.

49
00:03:34,076 --> 00:03:38,700
The exact hostnames and official host-key fingerprints must come from RCC administrators.

50
00:03:38,700 --> 00:03:42,938
Do not accept a changed fingerprint merely because a dialog appears.

51
00:03:42,938 --> 00:03:48,333
A changed key can indicate a rebuilt host, a configuration issue, or an attack.

52
00:03:48,333 --> 00:03:54,499
Test the route in a normal terminal and record the exact error message if it fails.

53
00:03:54,499 --> 00:03:57,614
Visual Studio Code is not itself the cluster.

54
00:03:57,614 --> 00:04:04,622
The window runs locally, but the Remote - SSH extension opens a workspace on the RCC submission host.

55
00:04:04,622 --> 00:04:07,737
A colored remote indicator shows the active connection.

56
00:04:07,737 --> 00:04:12,409
The Explorer then lists remote files, and the integrated terminal starts remotely.

57
00:04:12,409 --> 00:04:17,471
Extensions may need a remote installation because some code runs near the files.

58
00:04:17,471 --> 00:04:24,868
Before editing, verify the remote indicator, run hostname in the terminal, and open the intended project directory rather than

59
00:04:24,868 --> 00:04:26,426
your entire home directory.

60
00:04:26,426 --> 00:04:29,930
Do not launch long analyses in the integrated terminal.

61
00:04:29,930 --> 00:04:35,770
Use Slurm, and use tmux only to protect the lightweight workflow controller or monitoring session.

62
00:04:35,770 --> 00:04:40,815
Interactive SSH is optimized for commands, not for moving large biomedical datasets.

63
00:04:40,815 --> 00:04:46,280
The approved browser transfer service provides a managed path for uploads and downloads.

64
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:53,006
Use a project directory agreed with your group, not a random folder in your home directory.

65
00:04:53,006 --> 00:04:57,210
Transfer only data permitted by the project and institutional policy.

66
00:04:57,210 --> 00:05:05,197
For a small training file, calculate a SHA two fifty-six checksum locally, upload the file, calculate the checksum on

67
00:05:05,197 --> 00:05:07,299
RCC, and compare the values.

68
00:05:07,299 --> 00:05:10,662
Matching checksums show that the bytes are identical.

69
00:05:10,662 --> 00:05:18,650
For clinical or identifiable data, follow the approved data-protection process rather than improvising with personal cloud storage or email.

70
00:05:18,650 --> 00:05:20,550
Slurm is the resource manager.

71
00:05:20,550 --> 00:05:26,631
Instead of choosing a compute node yourself, you describe the resources required by a job: time,

72
00:05:26,631 --> 00:05:28,912
CPUs, memory, and sometimes a GPU.

73
00:05:28,912 --> 00:05:35,753
Slurm queues the job, finds a suitable node, starts the job, records its state, and releases resources afterwards.

74
00:05:35,753 --> 00:05:37,654
The request should be realistic.

75
00:05:37,654 --> 00:05:43,735
Too little memory can kill the job; too much memory can delay scheduling and waste capacity.

76
00:05:43,735 --> 00:05:49,056
A batch script is a plain text record of the command and requested resources.

77
00:05:49,056 --> 00:05:54,377
That makes it easier to repeat, audit, and share than an undocumented interactive session.

78
00:05:54,377 --> 00:05:56,861
The first job should be deliberately simple.

79
00:05:56,861 --> 00:06:02,893
Create a working directory and a batch script that requests one CPU, a small amount of memory,

80
00:06:02,893 --> 00:06:04,312
and a few minutes.

81
00:06:04,312 --> 00:06:09,989
The script prints the hostname, creates a few numbers, and calculates a mean using standard tools.

82
00:06:09,989 --> 00:06:11,763
Submit it with s batch.

83
00:06:11,763 --> 00:06:13,537
Slurm returns a job identifier.

84
00:06:13,537 --> 00:06:20,278
Use s queue to see whether it is pending or running, and s acct after completion to inspect the

85
00:06:20,278 --> 00:06:20,988
final state.

86
00:06:20,988 --> 00:06:25,955
Open the output log and confirm that the hostname belongs to a compute node.

87
00:06:25,955 --> 00:06:29,503
The important lesson is the job lifecycle, not the arithmetic.

88
00:06:29,503 --> 00:06:35,428
A normal SSH connection ends when the laptop sleeps, the network changes, or the terminal closes.

89
00:06:35,428 --> 00:06:39,501
T mux creates a persistent terminal session on the remote host.

90
00:06:39,501 --> 00:06:42,464
You can detach, disconnect, reconnect later, and reattach.

91
00:06:42,464 --> 00:06:48,388
This is useful for editing, monitoring, or running a Snakemake controller that submits jobs to Slurm.

92
00:06:48,388 --> 00:06:55,424
It does not grant more compute resources and it does not make it acceptable to run heavy analysis on

93
00:06:55,424 --> 00:06:56,535
the login host.

94
00:06:56,535 --> 00:07:02,459
A good mental model is that tmux preserves the steering wheel, while Slurm provides the engine.

95
00:07:02,459 --> 00:07:06,533
Name sessions clearly and close them when the work is complete.

96
00:07:06,533 --> 00:07:13,199
You are ready to continue when you can demonstrate each outcome rather than merely following the steps once.

97
00:07:13,199 --> 00:07:16,903
You can identify whether a terminal is local or remote.

98
00:07:16,903 --> 00:07:20,977
You can explain the difference between your private and public keys.

99
00:07:20,977 --> 00:07:23,569
You have verified the official server fingerprint.

100
00:07:23,569 --> 00:07:26,162
Command-line SSH works before Visual Studio Code.

101
00:07:26,162 --> 00:07:29,124
You can open the correct remote project directory.

102
00:07:29,124 --> 00:07:33,198
You can transfer a small non-sensitive file and match its checksum.

103
00:07:33,198 --> 00:07:40,235
You can submit a batch script, observe its job identifier, and confirm that it completed on a compute node.

104
00:07:40,235 --> 00:07:45,050
Keep the commands and logs; they are useful evidence when asking for support.

